Ask HN: Recommendations on trying to write a efficient text editor
text: For a while now, I've been writing a small text editor. The idea is that I have a basic mvp that I can add to here and there. Currently I'm writing it in c++ using SDL2 to render and using a doubly linked list of gap buffers to store the text. At the moment it's not as performant as I'd like it to be and I've been wondering if there's more efficient ways to store text and render it. Maybe my question sounds stupid, but is there lightweight libraries out there to render text and get keyboard input FAST? In the same vein, is there better more efficient ways of storing text other than using a linked list of gap buffers?

Ask HN: Proposed HNDM Design
text: Suppose that HN user Foo wishes to DM user Bar. HN knows their real email addresses, so Foo emails Bar@hndm.com, and HNDM auto-forwards this to Bar's real email address. If Foo wants a response from Bar, Foo needs to tell Bar their (Foo's) real email address, and Bar can email them directly. The only accepted/understood direct reply to one of these forwards is "block", which will forever block Foo from sending to Bar. If Foo gets three blocks, they're disallowed from sending HNDMs until the they are under three blocks, which clear at one block/week.
